	        		        	<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Crypto:PRG security definitions</h1>
				<div id="bodyContent">
		            <h3 id="siteSub">From Coursera</h3>
		            <div id="contentSub"></div>
		            		            		            					<!-- start content -->
					<div lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><p>$$ Let G:K\rightarrow \lbrace 0,1\rbrace^n\ be\ a\ PRG$$</p>
<p><u>Goal:</u> define what it means for the output of a generator to be indistinguishable from random. In other words, we're gonna define a distribution that basically is defined by choosing a random key in the key space.</p>
<h3> <span class="mw-headline" id="Statistical_Tests">Statistical Tests</span></h3>
<p><u>Statistical test:</u> on {0,1}<sup>n</sup>: an algorithm A s.t. A(x) outputs 0 (not random) or 1 (random)</p>
<p><b>Examples:</b></p>
<ul>
<li>For a random string the number of zeros is roughly the same as the number of ones.</li>
<li>Similar we can set a limit on the number of double zero sequences</li>
<li>Count the longest series of zeros (should be less than 10 x log(n))</li>
</ul>
<h3> <span class="mw-headline" id="Advantage">Advantage</span></h3>
<p>Let $$G:\; \mathcal{K} \rightarrow \lbrace 0, 1 \rbrace^n$$ be a PRG and $$A$$ a statistical test on $$\lbrace 0, 1 \rbrace^n$$.</p>
<p>Define $$\text{Adv}&#95;{\scriptsize \text{PRG}}[A, G] = \left\lvert \mathop{\large \text{Pr}}\limits&#95;{k \overset{\scriptsize R}{\leftarrow} \mathcal{K}} \left[ A(G(k)) = 1 \right]\; - \mathop{\large \text{Pr}}\limits&#95;{r \overset{\scriptsize R}{\leftarrow} \left\lbrace 0, 1 \right\rbrace^{\scriptsize n}} \left[ A(r) = 1 \right] \right\rvert \in [0, 1]$$</p>
<h3> <span class="mw-headline" id="Security_and_Predictability_are_equivalent">Security and Predictability are equivalent</span></h3>

